The use of TEA alone does not provide an unequivocal result because it can be argued that TEA was acting to block the delayed rectifier which repolarizes nerve fibre action potentials. If this were the case then TEA ought to have clear effects in the presence of Cd2+, when any Ca2+-dependent K+ events have been abolished. Therefore, we compared the action of low concentrations of TEA (< 500 /,M) in the

