produced a slight but distinct broadening of the action potential. It is therefore impossible to be certain that these low concentrations of TEA act solely on the Ca2+-dependent K+ current (see Discussion). In accord with this we found that much higher concentrations of TEA (10-20 mM) than were necessary to abolish the fast a.h.p. could indeed be demonstrated to cause a large, and reversible, increase in the width of the action potential in the presence of 200 ,mM-Cd2+.

